## Feature Request
<!--
High level description of the requested feature or improvement.
-->
It should be theoretically possible to pause a stream. The end goal of this would be to save compute by allowing users to pause and resume streams at will.

By using a `tokio::sync::watch::channel` with a bool type, we can control the flow of a stream. See below for a (ChatGPT-generated) example of this in action:

```rust
struct PauseableStream {
    paused_rx: watch::Receiver<bool>,
    counter: usize,
}

impl Stream for PauseableStream {
    type Item = usize;

    fn poll_next(mut self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<Option<Self::Item>> {
        if *self.paused_rx.borrow() {
            // Register the task to be notified when the paused value changes.
            let _ = self.paused_rx.changed();
            cx.waker().wake_by_ref(); // try polling again later
            Poll::Pending
        } else {
            let val = self.counter;
            self.counter += 1;
            Poll::Ready(Some(val))
        }
    }
}
```

### Motivation
<!--
Please describe the use case(s) or other motivation for the new feature.
-->
Better overall control over streamed responses

